To develop a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file, you can follow these steps:

1. Include the necessary header files.
2. Open the file for reading.
3. Read the file line by line.
4. For each line, tokenize it into words.
5. Compare each word with the target word and increment the count if they match.
6. Close the file.
7. Print the count.

Here's a sample C++ code to achieve this:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

int main() {
    std::string filename = "example.txt"; // Replace with your file name
    std::string target_word = "word"; // Replace with the word you want to count
    std::ifstream file(filename);
    std::string line;
    int word_count = 0;

    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error: Unable to open the file." << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        std::istringstream iss(line);
        std::string word;

        while (iss >> word) {
            // Remove punctuation from the word for better matching (optional)
            word.erase(std::remove_if(word.begin(), word.end(), ::ispunct), word.end());

            if (word == target_word) {
                word_count++;
            }
        }
    }

    file.close();
    std::cout << "The word \"" << target_word << "\" appears " << word_count << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Make sure to replace `"example.txt"` with the path to your text file and `"word"` with the word you want to count.

This code uses `std::ifstream` to read the file, `std::getline` to read lines, `std::istringstream` to tokenize lines into words, and a simple comparison to count the occurrences of the target word. It also includes an optional step to remove punctuation from words for better matching.
